Produce comprehensive 1:1 meeting notes using every section below. For each section, extract ALL relevant information from the transcript. If a topic was not discussed, write "Not discussed in this meeting."

## Title
[Specific, descriptive title — 3 to 10 words. NOT "Weekly 1:1" — name the actual topics discussed.]

## Summary
[3-5 sentences: what was discussed, key outcomes, any concerns raised, overall tone of the meeting]

## Mood & Energy Check-in
[How did the employee seem? Did they express how they're feeling about work? Note any self-reported happiness/energy level, work-life balance comments, stress indicators, or enthusiasm. If the employee mentioned how their week/sprint has been going, capture it here. Note the tone — were they upbeat, flat, frustrated, energized?]

## Accomplishments & Wins
[EVERY accomplishment, completed task, or win the employee mentioned since the last meeting. Be specific with dates, project names, and outcomes where mentioned. Include:]
- Completed work items with specific details
- Problems solved or incidents handled
- Positive feedback received from peers, stakeholders, or customers
- Milestones reached on longer-term projects
- Any initiative or ownership demonstrated beyond their core role

## Progress Against Objectives
[How is the employee tracking against their goals/OKRs/objectives? Capture:]
- Which objectives were discussed
- Current status or percentage complete for each
- Timeline changes (ahead/behind/on track)
- Obstacles to hitting targets
- Any new objectives or goal adjustments discussed
[If no formal objectives were discussed, note any implicit progress discussion.]

## Blockers & Challenges
[Identify ALL blockers and challenges mentioned. For EACH blocker, capture: what the blocker is, how the employee is currently handling it, and what support they need from the manager.]

### Operational Blockers
[Day-to-day issues: system outages, access problems, tooling failures, deployment issues, on-call burden, incident response gaps, environment issues. For each: what is it, how are they handling it, what do they need?]

### Organizational Blockers
[People/process issues: unclear ownership, cross-team dependencies, approval bottlenecks, communication gaps, staffing shortages, unclear priorities, meeting overload. For each: what is it, how are they handling it, what do they need?]

### Physical / Infrastructure Blockers
[Hardware, network, data center, equipment, office/remote setup, connectivity issues.]

### Roadmap / Strategic Blockers
[Product direction, feature prioritization, technical debt, architecture decisions, migration timelines, vendor decisions blocking progress.]

## Feedback Given (Manager → Employee)
[ALL feedback the manager gave during this meeting. Use SBI format where possible:]
- **Positive feedback**: What was recognized? Be specific about the situation, behavior, and impact.
- **Constructive feedback**: What improvement areas were discussed? What specific examples were given? What was the agreed approach to improve?
[This section is critical for performance review documentation. Capture exact examples.]

## Feedback Received (Employee → Manager/Org)
[ALL feedback the employee gave upward — about the manager's style, team processes, organizational decisions, leadership, tools, culture. This is often subtle — capture it even when expressed indirectly as complaints, suggestions, or observations.]

## Service & Technology Feedback
[Capture ALL feedback about services, tools, and platforms discussed.]

### AWS Services
[Feedback on EC2, S3, Lambda, EKS, SageMaker, Bedrock, Control Tower, Security Hub, IAM, CloudFormation, etc. Include: satisfaction, pain points, feature requests, cost concerns, performance issues.]

### NetApp Services
[Feedback on ONTAP, Cloud Volumes, StorageGRID, BlueXP, Astra, FSx for NetApp ONTAP, etc. Include: satisfaction, pain points, feature requests, performance issues.]

### Other Services & Tools
[Feedback on Jira, Confluence, Slack, GitHub, CI/CD, monitoring tools, internal platforms, etc.]

## Customer & Stakeholder Feedback
[What did the employee share about customer interactions, stakeholder relationships, or external feedback? Include: customer satisfaction signals, complaints relayed, feature requests heard, relationship health.]

## Team & Organization Observations
[What did the employee observe or comment about: team dynamics, morale, collaboration, process friction, culture, recent org changes, strategy clarity? These observations are valuable signals about the broader team health.]

## Career Development & Growth
[Everything discussed about the employee's career trajectory:]
- Short-term skill goals and learning interests
- Long-term career aspirations
- Desired projects, stretch assignments, or role changes
- Training/certification needs or completed milestones
- Mentoring relationships (giving or receiving)
- Readiness signals for promotion or role expansion

## Coaching Notes
[If any coaching conversation happened, capture:]
- What was the topic/challenge being coached on?
- What options or approaches were explored?
- What was the agreed next step?
- What commitments did the employee make for self-improvement?

## Engagement & Wellbeing Signals
[Note any signals — positive or concerning — about the employee's engagement level. Be factual, not judgmental.]

### Positive Signals
[Volunteering ideas, enthusiasm about projects, discussing future plans at the company, taking initiative, mentoring others, asking about growth opportunities.]

### Concerning Signals
[Short/minimal answers, low energy, cynicism, "not my job" attitude (if new), expressing dissatisfaction with role/compensation/growth, withdrawal from team activities, mentions of burnout or overwhelm, signs of checking out.]

[If no clear signals either way, write "No notable signals in this meeting."]

## Decisions Made
[All decisions, with who made them and the rationale]

## Action Items
[EVERY commitment made by either person. Separate manager and employee actions.]

